    <h2>About Adam Broomberg and Oliver Chanarin</h2>
 

  <p>Adam Broomberg and Oliver Chanarin are a photographic team based in London. They met in Wuppetal, a mission town in the Western Cape of South Africa and have been friends ever since. They started taking photographs together because they only had one camera. That was seven years ago. Since then the duo have been busy.</p>

<p>After publishing their first book, Trust - a photographic monograph that accompanied their solo show at the Hasselblad Centre in Sweden - they were charged with the task of re-launching Benetton�s Colors Magazine. As the editors and principle photographers they spent three years in the job. The result was a second book, GHETTO, which is a photographic study of 12 closed communities around the world for which they received the prestigious Vic Oden Award from the Royal Society of Photographers in Great Britain. Last year Broomberg and Chanarin embarked on a new project. They were commissioned by the South African Government to produce a photographic document of contemporary South Africa ten years after the end of Apartheid. They returned to their homeland and for three months traversed the country, talking to people and collecting stories about South Africa�s transition to democracy. The result is a book, Mr. Mikhize�s Portrait, published to coincide with their solo exhibition at the Photographers Gallery in London. While in South Africa they also made their first documentary film for Channel Four.</p>

<p>Broomberg and Chanarin have exhibited their work at the Victoria and Albert Museum in London, The British National Museum of Photograph, The Africana Museum in Johannesburg, the Florence Photographic Biennale and the Johannesburg Art Gallery. Their photographs are also part of the Victoria and Albert Museum permanent collection.</p>

<p>The duo are regularly contributors to the Observer Magazine in London and teach workshops in photography.<br />
